{"title_page": "Martin Hall (academic)", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Martin Hall\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =         File:Professor Martin Hall.jpg<!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Martin Hall in 2003\n| caption     = Martin Hall in 2003\n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.corporate.salford.ac.uk/leadership-management/martin-hall/biography/|title=Biography: Professor Martin Hall|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> [[England]]\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = British and South African citizenship\n| fields      = [[Archaeology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n| workplaces  =  [[University of Cape Town]], [[University of Salford]]\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Chichester High School For Boys]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| thesis_title =        <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =         <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =         <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =    <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse      =        Brenda Cooper <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner     =         <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = \n| signature   =         <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =         {{URL|martinhallfacilitation.org}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Martin Hall''' (born in [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\"/> [[England]]) is a British-South African academic and educationalist who has written extensively on [[South African history]], culture and higher education policy. He is a former Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]].<ref name=biography/>\n\n==Early life==\nHall studied at [[Chichester High School For Boys]], one of the two state schools in the United Kingdom at the time that prepared students for [[Oxbridge]] admission.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Ready for a chilly winter|accessdate=2009-09-23 | location=London | first=Linda | last=Nordling | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> He was the first in his family to complete university.<ref name=guardian/> He completed his bachelor's degree in [[archaeology]] and [[anthropology]] at [[Cambridge University]] in 1974.<ref name=\"UCTCV\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]] |url=http://www.uct.ac.za/downloads/email/ABBREVIATED_CV_hall_final_19072007.pdf |title=CV: Professor Martin Hall |accessdate=2009-09-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe worked firstly in [[Lesotho]] in the area of archaeological excavation and then in London for the Southwark Archaeological Rescue Unit. He moved to South Africa in 1975 where he worked for five years as an [[Ethnoarchaeology|ethnoarchaeologist]] in the Natal Museum in [[Pietermaritzburg]]. He completed his doctoral studies at Cambridge in 1980<ref name=UCTCV/> and moved to [[Cape Town]] in the same year. He then became Chief Professional Officer for the Department of Archaeology at the [[South African Museum]].<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\n==University of Cape Town==\nHe joined the [[University of Cape Town]] Department of Archaeology in 1983 and was promoted from Associate Professor to Professor of Historical Archaeology,<ref name=\"dvc-cand\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|title=Five candidates shortlisted for DVC posts|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615174926/http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming in due course the head of department. In 1983 he became Director of the Centre for African Studies<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\nHe was Director of the Multimedia Education Group from 1997\u20132001 at UCT.\n\nIn 1998, he was appointed as a Fellow of the University of Cape Town, and the following year became the inaugural Dean of the Higher Education Development Unit,<ref name=UCTCV/> charged with coordinating support for students from underprivileged backgrounds.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1999 he was appointed as President of the [[World Archaeological Congress]]<ref name=dvc-cand/> and also served as General Secretary of the South African Archaeological Society.\n\nIn 2002 he was promoted to deputy vice-chancellor<ref name=UCTCV/> and held this position for six years with responsibilities for strategic, academic and budget planning. He stepped down from this position at the end of August 2008 to take up a position at the Graduate School of Business.<ref name=\"uctpress\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/dailynews/archives/?id=6872|title=Martin Hall to take the helm at Salford|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of South Africa]].<ref name=dvc-cand/>\n\nHe is part of Flooved advisory board.\n\n==University of Salford==\nShort-listed for the position of Chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Ahmherst, Hall was however unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/hall-offers-outsiders-perspective-chancellors-job|title=Hall offers outsider's perspective to chancellor's job|website=Office of News & Media Relations &#124; UMass Amherst}}</ref> He was to be appointed a few months later, in October 2008, as the next vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"salfordvc\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|title=Salford University appoints Vice-Chancellor from South Africa|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805224156/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|archive-date=5 August 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Interview: Martin Hall, new vice-chancellor of Salford University|first=Linda|last=Nordling|date=25 November 2008|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> He arrived at Salford in April 2009 as vice-chancellor designate and officially took up the post on 1 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://staff.salford.ac.uk/newsitem/983|title=\"New VC Designate arrives at University of Salford\"|publisher=[[University of Salford]]}}</ref> Hall stated in June 2013 that Salford had had \"too aggressive an industrial-relations stance in previous years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/salfords-vice-chancellors-candid-mea-culpa/2004767.article|title=\"Salford\u2019s vice-chancellor\u2019s candid mea culpa\"|date=13 June 2013|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHall holds joint British and South African citizenship.<ref name=salfordvc/> His wife, Professor Brenda Cooper, is an academic specialising in post-colonial and African literature. They have three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*Hall, Martin 2000. \u201cArchaeology and the Modern World: Colonial Transcripts in South Africa and the Chesepeake\u201c London: Routledge {{ISBN|0-415-22966-9}}\n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNothing is different but everything\u2019s changed\u201d. In The Next Twenty Five Years? Affirmative Action and Higher Education in the United States and South Africa. \n*Edited by Martin Hall, Marvin Krislov and David L. Featherman. University of Michigan Press. \n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNew knowledge and the university\u201d. Anthropology Southern Africa, 32 (1 and 2): 69-86.\n\n==External links==\n* {{SAHRA people | martin-hall | Martin Hall }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box|title=Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]]|years=2009&ndash;2015|before=[[Michael Harloe]]|after=[[Helen Marshall (academic)|Helen Marshall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Martin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African archaeologists]]\n[[Category:South African educational theorists]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town academics]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Guildford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Martin Hall\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =         File:Professor Martin Hall.jpg<!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Martin Hall in 2003\n| caption     = Martin Hall in 2003\n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.corporate.salford.ac.uk/leadership-management/martin-hall/biography/|title=Biography: Professor Martin Hall|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> [[England]]\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = British and South African citizenship\n| fields      = [[Archaeology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n| workplaces  =  [[University of Cape Town]], [[University of Salford]]\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Chichester High School For Boys]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| thesis_title =        <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =         <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =         <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =    <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse      =        Brenda Cooper <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner     =         <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = \n| signature   =         <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =         {{URL|martinhallfacilitation.org}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Martin Hall''' (born in [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\"/> [[England]]) is a British-South African academic and educationalist who has written extensively on [[South African history]], culture and higher education policy. He is a former Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]].<ref name=biography/>\n\n==Early life==\nHall studied at [[Chichester High School For Boys]], one of the two state schools in the United Kingdom at the time that prepared students for [[Oxbridge]] admission.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Ready for a chilly winter|accessdate=2009-09-23 | location=London | first=Linda | last=Nordling | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> He was the first in his family to complete university.<ref name=guardian/> He completed his bachelor's degree in [[archaeology]] and [[anthropology]] at [[Cambridge University]] in 1974.<ref name=\"UCTCV\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]] |url=http://www.uct.ac.za/downloads/email/ABBREVIATED_CV_hall_final_19072007.pdf |title=CV: Professor Martin Hall |accessdate=2009-09-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe worked firstly in [[Lesotho]] in the area of archaeological excavation and then in London for the Southwark Archaeological Rescue Unit. He moved to South Africa in 1975 where he worked for five years as an [[Ethnoarchaeology|ethnoarchaeologist]] in the Natal Museum in [[Pietermaritzburg]]. He completed his doctoral studies at Cambridge in 1980<ref name=UCTCV/> and moved to [[Cape Town]] in the same year. He then became Chief Professional Officer for the Department of Archaeology at the [[South African Museum]].<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\n==University of Cape Town==\nHe joined the [[University of Cape Town]] Department of Archaeology in 1983 and was promoted from Associate Professor to Professor of Historical Archaeology,<ref name=\"dvc-cand\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|title=Five candidates shortlisted for DVC posts|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615174926/http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming in due course the head of department. In 1983 he became Director of the Centre for African Studies<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\nHe was Director of the Multimedia Education Group from 1997\u20132001 at UCT.\n\nIn 1998, he was appointed as a Fellow of the University of Cape Town, and the following year became the inaugural Dean of the Higher Education Development Unit,<ref name=UCTCV/> charged with coordinating support for students from underprivileged backgrounds.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1999 he was appointed as President of the [[World Archaeological Congress]]<ref name=dvc-cand/> and also served as General Secretary of the South African Archaeological Society.\n\nIn 2002 he was promoted to deputy vice-chancellor<ref name=UCTCV/> and held this position for six years with responsibilities for strategic, academic and budget planning. He stepped down from this position at the end of August 2008 to take up a position at the Graduate School of Business.<ref name=\"uctpress\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/dailynews/archives/?id=6872|title=Martin Hall to take the helm at Salford|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of South Africa]].<ref name=dvc-cand/>\n\nHe is part of Flooved advisory board.\n\n==University of Salford==\nShort-listed for the position of Chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Ahmherst, Hall was however unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/hall-offers-outsiders-perspective-chancellors-job|title=Hall offers outsider's perspective to chancellor's job|website=Office of News & Media Relations &#124; UMass Amherst}}</ref> He was to be appointed a few months later, in October 2008, as the next vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"salfordvc\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|title=Salford University appoints Vice-Chancellor from South Africa|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805224156/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|archive-date=5 August 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Interview: Martin Hall, new vice-chancellor of Salford University|first=Linda|last=Nordling|date=25 November 2008|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> He arrived at Salford in April 2009 as vice-chancellor designate and officially took up the post on 1 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://staff.salford.ac.uk/newsitem/983|title=\"New VC Designate arrives at University of Salford\"|publisher=[[University of Salford]]}}</ref> Hall stated in June 2013 that Salford had had \"too aggressive an industrial-relations stance in previous years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/salfords-vice-chancellors-candid-mea-culpa/2004767.article|title=Salford\u2019s vice-chancellor\u2019s candid mea culpa|date=13{{cite web| June 2013|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHall holds joint British and South African citizenship.<ref name=salfordvc/> His wife, Professor Brenda Cooper, is an academic specialising in post-colonial and African literature. They have three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*Hall, Martin 2000. \u201cArchaeology and the Modern World: Colonial Transcripts in South Africa and the Chesepeake\u201c London: Routledge {{ISBN|0-415-22966-9}}\n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNothing is different but everything\u2019s changed\u201d. In The Next Twenty Five Years? Affirmative Action and Higher Education in the United States and South Africa. \n*Edited by Martin Hall, Marvin Krislov and David L. Featherman. University of Michigan Press. \n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNew knowledge and the university\u201d. Anthropology Southern Africa, 32 (1 and 2): 69-86.\n\n==External links==\n* {{SAHRA people | martin-hall | Martin Hall }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box|title=Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]]|years=2009&ndash;2015|before=[[Michael Harloe]]|after=[[Helen Marshall (academic)|Helen Marshall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Martin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[